(1879, 1, '2012-05-28 09:56:02', '2012-05-28 13:56:02', '<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah I can hear you.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi:<strong> </strong>Record it, Jack.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah I pressed start. It’s recording. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Alright.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay Pops. Uhhh... (pause) Basic interview scrip...Interview must be 45 minutes longer. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Go on. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, where were you living during World War II? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Rockhampton, Central Queensland, Australia. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: R-O-C-K...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Haha I know Poppy.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: (Laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: *Laugh* Wait, Wasn’t Rockhampton the second largest city in Queensland at that time?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Possibly, that’s right. It was at one time. Yes, possibly. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Well...umm...what’s there...what’s famous there?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They...they refer to it as today the beef capital of Australia so there was a lot of beef... Beef cattle industry. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh I see... I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But more in the inland and the surrounding districts, I should think.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm... How old were you at the time?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ahh... </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I mean when it began... It began in 1941 right? Or something like that...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, World War II in Europe commenced in 1939...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, in 1939. Okay...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and I would have been three in the November.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay so three...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I was only two when the war started. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay... How about when it ended? August 1945.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: August 1945... So I was eight! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Eight when it ended? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Correct. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay. Wait, Pops, how old are you right now? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I am seventy-five! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: You are seventy-five now... Okay. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Correct. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, alright. Umm... Who were you living with? ...at the time. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother and two brothers. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh yeah yeah, </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother and two brothers. That’s Nanna Balaam. You remember her. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah... </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So with my mother and two brothers who were younger than I am. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wait, wher...how about your dad? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He was not away in the war, but he was uhh... the word was I suppose... conscripted because he was a cabinet maker...he had to built accommodation for the American troops...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh... Where was he sent... Where did they send him?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Townsville, North Queensland</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Towns...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He was in Townsville, North Queensland...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh okay...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And Brisbane, I think. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh really?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Brisbane at some time...yes... Yes he was. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Was he, Bernie? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Bernice Balaam (Nan): Yes, he was. </em></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He was in Townsville and Brisbane. At the best of my knowledge. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, what was your occupation?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Who’s occupation?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Your occupation.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I was a school boy at that point. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: School student ... (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Is that what you mean? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, which school did you attend?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...school boy.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Which school did you attend?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: St. Joseph’s Convent School </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: St. Joseph’s Convent School... (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: St. Joseph’s Convent School... </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Is it still here? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The school is still there but there are no more nuns there...anymore.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, so what is it know? It’s not a Catholic school anymore?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah but it’s staffed by lay people.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh I see...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It is still a Catholic school but there aren’t any nuns. You know, there are a few nuns around but its...still a Catholic school at the same site. S-I-T-E. Same site. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see. Um...so what grade were you in? What...like...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I came in school at the beginning of 1942</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: 1942...okay.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I began school in 1942.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: How was...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And they weren’t called “grades”, they were called “preps.” P-R-E-P-S. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, preps. Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Short for “preparatory.” </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, preps. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We had two preps in a year. At that year I was in prep 1 and after six months you went into prep 2.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh really?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Then the next year you will be in prep 3 and then prep 4. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Then you went into grade 1.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhhhh. So is it kinda like kindergarden? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...No, no. You learnt things. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahhh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were learning the alphabet. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: K, and like 1+1? Addition and stuff?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ohh, vaguely. Things like “A for apple, B for bat”, you know, that sort of thing. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: C... I forget what C was for. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Did you guys learn about the war? Or did you...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sorry?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Did you guys know like...did the teachers talk about the war and stuff?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No. I wouldn’t say. I don’t remember the teachers talking about the war but we had...we had airway practice everyday.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What is that?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Airway practice at about 12 o’clock. Well, it was to prepare us in the event of enemy planes coming over with the intention of dropping bombs. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh. Everyday?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Everyday at 12 o’clock...well regularly, it might be everyday. I still remember it. And the nun who was in charge...a sister who was in charge stood... *laugh* you know at the top of the staircase, blow the whistle, and all us kids will race down the stairs like that...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Jump into these open trenches, which were dug in the school grounds.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If a plane ever came and dropped a bomb, and landed on us, that will be it. I wouldn’t be here today. *laugh*</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) But, luckily did the..No enemy planes...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, Rockhampton. Rockhampton didn’t...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: But like...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Rockhampton: ...was never a subject to any enemy...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Only like Darwin right?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, that is correct. But we were practicing in case. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, I see. Well, the Ame-Americans were actually in Queensland as well?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They were. They were at a place called Parkhurst. P-A-R-K-H-U-R-S-T. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Which was... It’s now a suburb of Rockhampton but in those days, it was like a... On the fringes of... On the fringes of the city. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh I see, I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A little bit out. It wasn’t way out but is now a suburb. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So it was really only probably three or four miles out of the city and they had a big army camp there.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm... I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: (Says something that cannot be understood)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, how...pa-pa-pa-pa-pa umm. Was it difficult to find food during the war? How did you find...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Food was rationed but we were never really without. We were never really without food like there wasn’t the circumstance where you just couldn’t buy...couldn’t buy meat. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah I get it. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But it was rationed and we were issued with what they called, “ration books” </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ration books?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ration books and the books had little coupons, tiny little coupons in them. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The page..the page was numbered. You know? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and each week, you were allowed or you were allocated so many coupons.  </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhhhh, I see. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If you want to make a note, if you want to make a note of this, the foods that were rationed, correct me if I’m wrong (</em>talking to Nan), <em>the foods that were rationed were meat...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Meat, yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...butter,</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Butter.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...tea,</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Tea. Also tea?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...sugar...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Cinnamon? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I beg your pardon. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What did you say before? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sugar, sugar, just “sugar”. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh “sugar.” Not cinnamon. (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: meat...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Meat, butter, tea, sugar...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...tea, sugar</em><strong>.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Clothing. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, clothing. Okay. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Everyone always had lots of clothing coupons over because they didn’t have the money to buy the clothing. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ah, yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Had surplus. They always had surplus...surplus clothing tickets. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and I still remember, we always ran out of butter...at...like on a Sunday... </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and the new coupons start till Monday. (giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother used to send me ‘round to these people like the (Nan coughing in the background) ahh... At the what we call a “corner store.” We used to call it the “corner store.” </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Like a little convenient store right? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Like a little convenient store down the road from you. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You know that seven-eleven or whatever it is. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, “Family mart.” </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother...my mother would send me around cause the shops...the shops weren’t open everyday...then. B-but in those days, they were open...only open for about an hour late in the afternoon on a Sunday. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So I would go with a note to ask this lady if she could get us half-a-pound of butter in advance against next weeks coupons. (giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (giggle)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: (says something that cannot be understood) Right?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and I would always use... I used to go to the butcher and I will hand the coupon numbers. My mother didn’t know, I used to handle all of that. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: She relied on me to know what the coupon numbers were. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And there were so many coupon numbers for a pound of meat and you know, that sort of thing. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Pop knew what the numbers were. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Smart.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I would have to take the coupons. I used to just take the catalogue, but I didn’t take the book, I don’t think. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (interrupts Pop) How...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: (says something)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: ...about...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...I knew what the coupon series was. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh. H-how about your brothers?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, they didn’t do anything ‘cause I was the eldest so I did that. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh Yeah. Uh-um Pops?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yes?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: So, it was meat, butter, tea, sugar, and clothing right? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Meat, butter, tea, sugar, and clothing, you’re right, that’s it. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: But no like...how ‘bout like flour and stuff?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No they were no rationing of flour, Bernie was there? (Nan says no) No, there were no rationing of flour, or fruit things but biscuits were not available. They were rationed. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So my uncle...my uncle was like a uhh, a department manager at a grocery store in the big grocery store... You know in the city of Rockhampton?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: So it was like uhh like Coles or Woolworths?  </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Uhh yes, a supermarket. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and when you go through, they had the biscuits under the counter, you know, hidden? (Mum laughs in the background)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and he’ll come up to the lady who served on the...like the checkout lady. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, yeah, yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and those days there was no scanning or anything, they just had to push, you know the old cash registers with the buttons? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: One shilling and six pence which was what they just ring that up and he come up and say to the woman on the till to give a packet of biscuits. We had to pay for it, you know, we were allowed to have a a packet of biscuits. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh lucky.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So he sorta, at his discretion. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They were available for everyone. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah so you guys got the secret...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and tin fruit. Tinned fruit, you know what we call “can fruit”? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What kind of fruit?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ah like can peaches and pairs. Can fruit was very scarce. </em>\r\n\r\n<em>  </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What? (Mum says “Sukunai” which means “few” in Japanese) Ohhh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You know, you buy a can of can fruit, don’t you? Or you might get them in bottles now.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I thought Queensland produced like...the amount of fruit...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Can pineapple and all that, yes. But it was all very difficult. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, ok. It was difficult. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t know. I think, I think that the...that sort of industry was perhaps restricted in to some extent. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Can fruit. These things were available but they were difficult, they were rationed. </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were very lucky. You didn’t have to have a coupon but you were very lucky to have one. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: So Pop, so you got your food at like just what do they call it, a supermarket? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was called a corner store. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Corner store...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A corner store. Or yes a supermarket which was called a “Cash and Carry.” C-A-S-H and carry, C-A-R-R-Y. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So you paid cash and carried your good away. (laugh) </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Cash and Carry. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You should be able to access on the computer. They were all called “Cash and Carry.”</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And this was a big store in Rockhampton. And there were only one or two in the main CBD of Rockhampton. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and a man used to ride a bicycle around the suburbs and take your order. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh! Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He would come...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Like a delivery service? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Exactly. He would come and take the order. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother said two pounds, because everything was in pounds and ounces at those days. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and he would come and she would say “two pounds of sugar” and he just knew all the prices off like that. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And he might say we got this going on this week and my mother would order and when she finished the order, he would add up the order and she paid and...he’d take the order away and later in the week, the delivery vehicle would come with the box of groceries and stuff.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That operates...operated all the time. It wasn’t exclusive to the war years. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But the other things about the scares of can fruit, biscuits and all that, ration of food were particularly relevant to the war years.  </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see. What was your favorite food, like type of food during the war, when you were a kid.  </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What made you like excited to have?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were not excited but well yes, we were always thought it was great to get this can fruit. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, can fruit?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: or these cream biscuits. They were delicacy. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and ice-cream because no one, very few people had refrigerators.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: or had what we called ice-chest. C-H-E-S-T. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ice-chest. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and you used to get a big box of ice delivered by the ice man. That kept all the perishable goods fresh.  </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (Accidentally music plays) oops! Oh ok. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The temperature in those ice-chests were never cold enough to...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: preserve? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...or store ice-cream, it will just melt. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, I see. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It’s like a refrigerator. So, we would go to the shop and buy and ice-cream cone. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Was there like an ice-cream man? Like you know the...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I think so, wasn’t there? Ice-cream man? No, no, you just went to the corner store and bought it.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You buy it in a ice-cream cone. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, yum.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...cone, you know?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Was there like vanilla ice-cream? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, maybe. Yeah you can get a penny or a... You can get a small cone for one penny which is a tiny little cone...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...or the standard size, single cone would cost three pence. Was that right Bernie? (Nan says yes.) Three pence which was about two cents. (Mum gasps) </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The other thing that you could buy, if you wanted it what was they used to be call it a “family brick” B-R-I-C-K, which was like a house brick, the size of that or a bit bigger. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So if you were having that as a treat, you will buy that and it was all wrapped up especially in a box. (Nan says “dry ice”) No, we never got it in dry ice. And we would go off and get it in the morning and you know you had to try and stop it from melting and you would cut it in to a...you could cut it in to slices. So you can get ice-cream in a cone, or in a “family brick.”</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, a family brick. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: B-R-I-C-K. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So that was all about at that time. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That was not exclusive to the war years but it was about that time.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That’s how you got ice-cream. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (Mum: I’m listening Dad, I’m on his couch. I’m here in his room.) </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What sort of changes did the war make in your lifestyle at the time? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well I was probably, I was probably too young because I was born just before the war started. I just lived that life and went to school everyday.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah so?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But in those early years, we only went to school everyday but we finished school at 12 o’clock. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wait, everyday which includes...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Everyday. A half day. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: But does that include Saturdays and Sundays?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, we never went on Saturday or Sunday. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And I don’t know whenever...I just don’t know why that was so. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh so, it’s not because of the war? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t know the reason for that, but that was in the catholic school but the state...public school...or state school had the class went for two and a half days. Two full days and the other half went for the remaining two and a half days. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I just don’t know why. What was your experience, Bernie? Did you have that? ...No Nan can’ remember that. But I distinctly remember.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, we had a fairly normal life. But we had to blacken the windows, that was something. That was the only thing. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Blacken the windows? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Blacken. B-L-A-C-K-E-N. Darken. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: How? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We had this a...a gray...like a...what would you call it...not felt...it’s like a gray cardboard-y soft cardboard. Gray soft cardboard. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...which had to be nailed. The windows were all wood in those days and not like your place, metal. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was timber windows. Like a gray, light cardboard, but you could tear it. It had to be nailed over the windows with all these little tacks. So at night time, when you put the lights on,</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? It won’t be seen from outside right?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...no one could see outside. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If there was a airway attack at night, the enemy would not be able to see.</em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...the house, you with me?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yes.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And they used to have local people going around as what they called, “air raid wardens.” Air raid wardens. W-A-R-D-E-N-S. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Air raid wardens. (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Air raid wardens. So they would go around checking the area. You know, I don’t know how big of an area they had. But this man, he only lived about ohh...down our street. He knocked on our door one night to tell Nanna Balaam that he could see light through one of the windows. (giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh (Mum laughs)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If they see light, they will knock on your door so you will have to darken your house. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Ohhh. (laugh)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: How did I remember that...ha!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Funny!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) Wow.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Hmm.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Do you have any particular...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Other from that...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Other than that, to me it was just a normal life-style. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, ok. Normal life-style. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I do remember, like my mother and other women talking and they were sort of very concerned and frightened...and frightened the prospects of being invaded. You know? I mean I was a kid...as a kid I just remember that cause adults. We wouldn’t. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: At six or seven you wouldn’t be taking in all...but I do remember these women talking and being very I said afraid at the prospects of a...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Invasion?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...invasion. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: By the Japanese?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well yes, with all due respect. Japanese invasion. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Because the Germans weren’t going to invade. Too far. Japanese invasion and how would they be treated. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hm, um, um. (agreed)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I do remember my mother talking to these ladies once or twice. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Once only, really. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I can’t believe you still believe it Pops. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sorry?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I can’t believe you still remember it. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yes, I do. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Yeah, you have a good memory.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: You have a great memory! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well, I wouldn’t have remember what happened two weeks ago. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: A good long-term memory but a bad short-term memory.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well, I distinctly remember this. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I didn\'t make that up! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: No. I know. You are a good interviewee.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yes, thank you! Do you have any particular happy memories from war time? If so, would you like to share one with me?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Did the teacher wrote these? (whispers)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yes. (whispers)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well, no...uhh...yes. They were happy times because periodically, my father...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, oh came back from...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, who you never knew...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: he’d be allowed to come home on leave. (Says something that cannot be understood)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Came back how many times? I’m sorry, when? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He would come home on leave. Just for a couple of days. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Leave?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Leave. L-E-A-V-E\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: </em>L-E-A-V-E. We say, “come home on leave.”\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh. Was it also like...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He’d be given time off the work.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. (typing) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ahhh. So, he’d come home. It might just be for a couple of days and I don’t think he was ever home for a week. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He was home for short periods. I don’t know for specific. He was home for short periods. </em>\r\n\r\n<em>. </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: How about like Christmas and stuff? Or like Easter?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No...not for specific. I can’t remember that. I...from my point of view, I always had Christmas school holidays out at my aunts. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. Christmas, school holidays... (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Your mother will remember. Aunt Stella. My Aunt Stella. S-T-E-L-L-A. Well just my aunt. I always had Christmas with her with a Christmas tree. But that was all the time. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I was ten, eleven, or twelve. It wasn’t confined to war years only. It was Christmas with her, I probably never had Christmas at home at all. I was always out at my aunties! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Where...where is your aunts? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh, she lived a suburb called Frenchville. F-R-E-N-C-H-V-I-L-L-E. Frenchville, which was those days, she lived about 2 miles up from the suburban area, up a bush road... It was in the bush. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Pass of Frenchville, cause they had the state school and everything there. Pass of Frenchville, well like suburban but it was getting into the outer suburbs. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Two miles further up this single gravel road. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So if you were singing along and you heard a car coming, you had to get off the road and go in the bush so that the car can pass. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was a single road. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Made out of gravel. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well that is not particular to the war years only. </em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah that is just when you are...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...getting back to the can fruit, she had this big stock up of can fruit...(giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Woah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Woah.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: She must have bought it before the war, during the war. (giggle) She used to have it hidden downstairs in a big cupboard. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) Did you steal...?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And every Sunday...I can still see this big box, it was a bog box. Tilt on its side. A big crate with a shelf and she had a piece of heshen, like a bag...heshen bag in front of it. H-E-S-H-E-N.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...that hid all the can goods she had. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and every Sunday, I’ll go down and bring back a, cause it had a high house, I’ll bring up a can of fruit and we would have that for our Sunday dessert! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Hahahaha.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh yeah? (laugh) Yum. (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: We take things for granted.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, how about a sad memory? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...oh. (pause) Well, not particularly of the war. I never had...I didn’t have any...no, I didn’t have any family members, or uncles or aunts because they were all...they were people who...oh yes, I did have an uncle! In World War II and he served in New Guinea but he came home safely. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So we didn’t have anyone wounded or killed like you hear about the different stories about the people on the Berber railway or...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I never knew anyone like that...ahh...the only...the only sad thing I could remember is this a...she would be a young woman in those days, maybe...maybe not even 20. I’m trying to think and she was going out with this American soldier. I don’t think she became engaged with him but she was going out with him and very fond of him and he was killed in the war. </em>\r\n\r\n<em>  </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...So I do remember that. She was Jean’s elder sister.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, that’s sad.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t remember whether she became engaged. I can’t remember. Anyhow, he was killed and she met someone else and got married and had a family. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yes, I remember that. That was sad. Because I have actually met this man. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and his name was Hank. H-A-N-K. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh! Hank...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Shane’s dog...\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. Do you remember seeing soldiers during the war? What countries did these soldiers come from? You’ve seen Americans soldiers. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...One day, a convoy of soldiers were passing through this suburb on Park Ave. where  I lived.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Convoy?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A convoy of soldiers, in the trucks. Like you see in these movies. You know, going through Germany in those war movies. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: In those trucks. Well, they were going in the backs of trucks like that. Ahh through this suburb. Down on the main street. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and I was on the footpath. I don’t know whether it was lunch time or I might have been coming home. I used to go home for my lunch because I used to live so close to the school. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I will go home for the main lunch. We rarely really took our lunch. We went home, most times. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Anyhow, they threw pennies to all the...they threw pennies, a whole hand full of pennies. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A penny would only be..equal to...be less than a cent. Right Bernie? A penny would be less than a cent. So they threw pennies and I think I managed to pick one up off the footpath. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Some kids got more than I did. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They scattered through. They threw pennies to us kids. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh. That’s nice. How about...what else? Only pennies? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...Yeah. I just only remember them giving pennies. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...hand full of pennies.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh. So, it was only American soldiers? No like British soldiers? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We didn’t see the British or any other Europeans. Because the British were all in Europe. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ah yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...or North Africa or whatever. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The only foreign troops that we ever had in Australia to my knowledge...and you could be able to confirm it, were the Americans. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok. Umm, the question is, “did you witness...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I’m sorry, did you witness what?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: “Did you witness any battles or violence?” But you haven’t right?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, no sorry. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It’s ok. (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, I have never witness anybody but I think they used to be, when you read about this, there were a certain amount of... And certainly in Brisbane...not up in Rockhampton...there were a certain amount of ill-feelings between the Australian and American troops.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What’s that?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sorry, you’re right?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: ...Ill-feelings? What? Sorry.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ill-feelings. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Bad feeling.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The Australians didn’t think too highly of the Americans...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhhh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The term is “ill-feelings” Meaning that they didn’t feel well...you know...because of all the young women were going out with the American soldiers. (giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: (laugh)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And you know, the Australians...they more had to take second place! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hahaha. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The Americans were, you know, entertaining the Australian women. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh..</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I mean I wasn’t exposed to that because I was a six, seven, or eight year old kid. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That wasn’t about me.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You know, I heard about that later.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh. I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So that’s not directly relevant. So the answer to that question is no. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I didn’t witness anything.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Are there any other stories from this time period that you would like to share with me? Anything else!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...No. I’m trying to think... Ahh. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Dad, did you tell Jack the reason why you don’t like sweet potato now?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh yeah! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh no. That does not have to do with the war. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That does not have to do with the war. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Ok, sorry.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, I’ll tell you that afterwards. I’m trying to think, the only thing I remember is one time, there was a well-known pilot, and he was flying this plane...I don’t know what kind of aircraft. But it was called G for George. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: G for George. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was well known. And he was a well known pilot. So he flew over Rockhampton. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (typing) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And he were out, just looking at this plane as it flew over. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and I mean really, if you Google, “G for George”, on the computer, you would probably find out about the story behind it. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t know.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I will look it up. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Was it called “G” or called “G for George”?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It’s called, “G for George”!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: (laugh)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: G for George!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, G for George!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: G for George. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: That’s cool.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, it’s not just called “G”. It’s called “G for George”!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Google, “G for George” and see what comes up!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, I will. I will google it. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It will be interesting because he was a well-known pilot at Park Ave. where we saw. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: G for George...I think I found it already! Wow. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Have you?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, G for George. Ok, it’s a...let’s see....I will read it. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Can you Google it while talking to me?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. Ok, “G for George flew 90 operational missions over Germany and occupied Europe during the height of the bomber offensive. From the time it was built in 1942 until its retirement from active service in 1944, the bomber was flown by Number 460 Squadron...” </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Squadron.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, squadron. R-A-A-F. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: R double A F which stand for the Royal Australian Air Force. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...(cannot be understood)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: A beg your pardon?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Does it say that it was particularly flown by any pilot? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, let’s see. Pilot... Um, Alec Saintsmith. Alec Saintsmith. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, the name doesn’t mean anything. But there, that’s it aircraft, it flew over! (giggles)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Wow! Ha!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Do you remember it Dad? Remember seeing it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yes! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: There is a photo with the Australian Prime Minister, Mr. Curtin?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Curtin. C-U-R-T-I-N. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh no. Harry Tickle. No I don’t know, he is the Grand Staff Engineer, responsible for the main...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Maintenance.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah...maintenance, for the bomber, G for George. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: There! I remembered something correctly!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I thought it might have been one, but it could be different pilots. That plane definitely flew over. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It was all over Germany right?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...so it must of made..come home to Australia and then because it was such a you know, well-known aircraft. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Today it is displayed in the Anzac Hall at the Australia War Memorial in Canberra. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh, is it? I would have to remember that!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I would have to go and see it.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Right, that was my little trip about that! G for George.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, thank you! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: What else do you want to ask?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Is there anything that you would like to tell the younger generations about your experience WW2 or about war in general?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well, I don’t have any...well I was a kid, you know...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You have asked me before...I forgot...I’ll answer this question now. No, I don’t particularly remember...anything that I sorta wanna pass on...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...as a child. My experiences were really normal and broad except that you know, things were a bit rationed but we were never hungry. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were never hungry, we just had to ration...and the good that we had were simple. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But then, yes, war in general...well, yes. War in general is...is just...how can I put it? It should not be contemplated. Just look at the war in Afghanistan, and the war in Iraq. And people are...you know....people have been...you know....people have been sent to war and the senseless slaughter and the loss of lives. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and on all sides. So, there is no reason for war. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...except if someone invaded a country, well then the people who are living there quite entitle to do something...to parts...bits of their country. To go off with you know whats the word...oh...to declare war on someone...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Self-defense isn’t it?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well I said in defense. There is no, yes, reason really...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam:...for war cause you know, just so many, so many innocent people and even the troops are killed and just look at it. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We just had Anzac Day which reminded us...reminds us of the senseless war....organized or determined by the British officers. They did not have much idea what they were doing quite frankly. People were just sent...as we say, lands to the slaughter. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: There is no real...no real...no reason for war. Things have to be resolved without war but as I said, the only thing is ahh...naturally, a country is invaded. Those people are entitled to try to defend themselves. They can’t just sit there and let the invader take their land. You know?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. I know what you mean. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The one you asked me before, you alright with that one?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A happy moment did you say, did you ask me some question about that somewhere along the...?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, I asked you, “What’s was one of the...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...happy memories. I remember when peace in the pacific was declared. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, when...(typing)...so that was August 15...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The war end on August 15, 1945. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, August 15, 1945. That is when the Japanese emperor spoke to the...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I remember that because, this lad...who lived around the corner in the next street, he was older than I am, rode a bicycle down our street...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...towing an empty kerosene can which was like a...would hold a... Four gallons, do you have things in gallons or liters over there in Japan?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Liters.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong><em>Brian Balaam: Liters. So, there was about...how many liters are in a gallon? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I will calculate it right now. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Roughly, roughly.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Three is it?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Four or something. Is it?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It’s ok...one liter is 0.26417 US gallons. Ok, wait, gallons to liters right? (door bell ringing) Ok Pops, it is 3.7 liters.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Isn’t it 3?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: 3.8 actually. 3.8 liters. (doorbell ringing again)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: one...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: One gallon is 3.8 liters. Roughly. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So in other words, the kerosene...so he was towing an empty 15 liter...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...on his bicycle. Just to make a noise...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...to celebrate that peace has arrived. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: So...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: This boy rode his bike down our street...a gravel street. So this empty kerosene drum which was a square, it was a square in those days which was big enough to carry 15~16 liters, it was bouncing off the back of his bike and this other younger lad was running behind him and we put up strings of paper flags. Those days, you couldn’t even get a flag, the Australian flag. You couldn’t get a flag during the war years made out of material.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So they were all paper flags. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, paper flags. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, made out of paper, you know?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So there were little paper flags in front of our house in Rockhampton on the front verandah between two posts flying...well they were just hanging like a banner, to celebrate peace. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So...I don’t think you are aware of it, originally, that date of August was called, “VJ Day” which stood for “Victory over Japan” </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: VJ Day.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: VJ Day, Victory over Japan. But more recent years, it was changed to try and be more sensitive to the Japanese, they changed it to VP Day which is Victory over the Pacific. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You with me?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. So Victory to Japan Day to Victory in the Pacific Day. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Victory over the Pacific, yes.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The other one is called the VE Day which is Victory in...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Europe!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...which would some time in was it in May?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yes, May. Let’s see. V...(Googling “VE Day”)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Did your mother get went to get the door?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. VE Day is um May 8th. But in Commonwealth countries it is May 7th. Why, I don’t know why. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We remember this as students at that time, students of a Catholic school, we always thought it was just one of those unusual things that victory in the Pacific was declared on the feast of the Assumption. The Assumption</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Feast of the Assumption. And you could look up the calendar in May, interesting, Europe was declared on the feast of the Assumption. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh so it’s...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You look it up!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A-S-S-U-M-P-T-I-O-N. </em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, victory...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So, victory in Europe was declared on the feast of the Assumption. Thereabouts. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, let’s see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The feast of the Assumptions...you know the nuns made a point of this at our Catholic school. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, haha.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I still remember that! I might be wrong, well I would have to access a Catholic calendar which you probably could. 1945 to find out when the feast of the Assumption was. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Let’s see. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Call that out. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Catholic calendar. Let’s see...I got a Catholic calendar. Catholic calendar...is it the Roman Catholic Saints...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: What?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Um... </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That will do. The Roman Catholic calendar... </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, let’s see. July...Feast in the...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: 1945 you gotta get cause the feast changes each year.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. Feast...1945. (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Noe you gotta get the Feast of the Assumption. A-S-S-U-M-P-T-I-O-N. Which date was it? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: 8th of July...wait...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, it’s not July...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wait, what are we trying to find again?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The Feast of the Assumption. A-S-S-P</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: -T-I-O-N. In 1945. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (typing) Ok, the Feast of the Assumption, 1945. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: What date?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It was...um...(pause) I can’t find it...May 20!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh, is it?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Something like that...yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh..well, we are wrong then. We were always told that is was close to the Feast of the Assumption. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wait, in 1945...um um um...yeah that’s it.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If you could look up Easter. When was Easter in 1945?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, Easter in 1945. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The Assumption is 40 days after Easter. I can work it out then. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, Easter 1945...was April 1st. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: April 1st?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup. Which means, it was the 21st? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sorry?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: In 1945, Easter Day was April the 1st. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Alright, so that is 30. There, that is 38 days. We are saying the Feast of the Assumption but it was close to it.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were always told that.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So that is what they saying, the...did they say the victory was the 8th of May? Was it? 1945.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, and I think that is when the kamikaze attacked...wait the kamikaze (Googling “kamikaze attacks”) You know Pops, when you were living Rockhampton, did you hear anything about what happened in...Darwin?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ahh...I don’t remember that.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: How many people died in Darwin? Let’s see...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, I don’t know. I can’t remember that, Jack. Sorry. (Skype sound)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Darwin...Japanese...attack (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I think there were 100 0r something. Weren\'t there? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: The bombing of Darwin. It was on February 19th, 1942. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, I don’t think...I think it was kept fairly quiet.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: “It was the first and the largest single attack by a foreign power against Australia.” </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That’s right.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, there were 240 Japanese aircraft attacked ships in Darwin’s harbor and umm...let’s see...how many people died?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was over 100 I think. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: 250~320 killed.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh, my goodness. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: ...and ten ships were sunk, 23 aircrafts destroyed...yeah. So, that’s it. That’s sad.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: How many ships sunk? How many ships were sunk?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh...ten. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Goodness.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: And 20 damaged. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They just celebrated...commemorated, not celebrated...the 70th anniversary, you see...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, really?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: In Darwin. Oh, yes. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Do they do that every year?</strong>\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: No, 70 years.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, yeah it is 70 years!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: It was 42 and now it is 2012 so...\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They may have an annual commemoration but this year was the 70th. And I don\'t remember hearing anything and I think the federal government kept it quiet so not to panic the people. I think you may find that, but I’m not sure. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, thank you!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My iPad is down to 17%, I have to go charge it. How is it going?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It’s good, it’s good. I just finished! Well, thank you for your time!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I’m not trying to get rid of you but I just looked up...I’m down to 16%, we would have to recharge. </em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, you should. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Is it ok? You asked everything?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You sure?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Very interesting Dad! (claps)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Thank you very much! (claps)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That’s alright!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Hurray!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Thank you Pops! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Hurray!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Thank you for your time! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', '', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1877-revision-2', '', '', '2012-05-28 09:56:02', '2012-05-28 13:56:02', '', 1877, 'http://localhost:8888/benmerde2012/2012/05/1877-revision-2/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ;
INSERT INTO `wp_lhejar_posts` ( `ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_category`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(1880, 1, '2012-05-28 09:56:10', '2012-05-28 13:56:10', '<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah I can hear you.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi:<strong> </strong>Record it, Jack.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah I pressed start. It’s recording. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Alright.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay Pops. Uhhh... (pause) Basic interview scrip...Interview must be 45 minutes longer. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Go on. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, where were you living during World War II? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Rockhampton, Central Queensland, Australia. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: R-O-C-K...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Haha I know Poppy.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: (Laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: *Laugh* Wait, Wasn’t Rockhampton the second largest city in Queensland at that time?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Possibly, that’s right. It was at one time. Yes, possibly. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Well...umm...what’s there...what’s famous there?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They...they refer to it as today the beef capital of Australia so there was a lot of beef... Beef cattle industry. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh I see... I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But more in the inland and the surrounding districts, I should think.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm... How old were you at the time?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ahh... </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I mean when it began... It began in 1941 right? Or something like that...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, World War II in Europe commenced in 1939...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, in 1939. Okay...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and I would have been three in the November.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay so three...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I was only two when the war started. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay... How about when it ended? August 1945.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: August 1945... So I was eight! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Eight when it ended? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Correct. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay. Wait, Pops, how old are you right now? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I am seventy-five! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: You are seventy-five now... Okay. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Correct. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, alright. Umm... Who were you living with? ...at the time. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother and two brothers. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh yeah yeah, </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother and two brothers. That’s Nanna Balaam. You remember her. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah... </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So with my mother and two brothers who were younger than I am. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wait, wher...how about your dad? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He was not away in the war, but he was uhh... the word was I suppose... conscripted because he was a cabinet maker...he had to built accommodation for the American troops...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh... Where was he sent... Where did they send him?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Townsville, North Queensland</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Towns...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He was in Townsville, North Queensland...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh okay...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And Brisbane, I think. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh really?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Brisbane at some time...yes... Yes he was. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Was he, Bernie? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Bernice Balaam (Nan): Yes, he was. </em></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He was in Townsville and Brisbane. At the best of my knowledge. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, what was your occupation?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Who’s occupation?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Your occupation.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I was a school boy at that point. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: School student ... (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Is that what you mean? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, which school did you attend?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...school boy.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Which school did you attend?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: St. Joseph’s Convent School </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: St. Joseph’s Convent School... (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: St. Joseph’s Convent School... </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Is it still here? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The school is still there but there are no more nuns there...anymore.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, so what is it know? It’s not a Catholic school anymore?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah but it’s staffed by lay people.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh I see...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It is still a Catholic school but there aren’t any nuns. You know, there are a few nuns around but its...still a Catholic school at the same site. S-I-T-E. Same site. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see. Um...so what grade were you in? What...like...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I came in school at the beginning of 1942</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: 1942...okay.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I began school in 1942.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: How was...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And they weren’t called “grades”, they were called “preps.” P-R-E-P-S. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, preps. Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Short for “preparatory.” </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, preps. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We had two preps in a year. At that year I was in prep 1 and after six months you went into prep 2.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh really?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Then the next year you will be in prep 3 and then prep 4. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Then you went into grade 1.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhhhh. So is it kinda like kindergarden? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...No, no. You learnt things. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahhh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were learning the alphabet. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: K, and like 1+1? Addition and stuff?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ohh, vaguely. Things like “A for apple, B for bat”, you know, that sort of thing. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: C... I forget what C was for. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Did you guys learn about the war? Or did you...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sorry?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Did you guys know like...did the teachers talk about the war and stuff?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No. I wouldn’t say. I don’t remember the teachers talking about the war but we had...we had airway practice everyday.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What is that?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Airway practice at about 12 o’clock. Well, it was to prepare us in the event of enemy planes coming over with the intention of dropping bombs. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh. Everyday?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Everyday at 12 o’clock...well regularly, it might be everyday. I still remember it. And the nun who was in charge...a sister who was in charge stood... *laugh* you know at the top of the staircase, blow the whistle, and all us kids will race down the stairs like that...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Jump into these open trenches, which were dug in the school grounds.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If a plane ever came and dropped a bomb, and landed on us, that will be it. I wouldn’t be here today. *laugh*</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) But, luckily did the..No enemy planes...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, Rockhampton. Rockhampton didn’t...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: But like...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Rockhampton: ...was never a subject to any enemy...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Only like Darwin right?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, that is correct. But we were practicing in case. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, I see. Well, the Ame-Americans were actually in Queensland as well?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They were. They were at a place called Parkhurst. P-A-R-K-H-U-R-S-T. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Which was... It’s now a suburb of Rockhampton but in those days, it was like a... On the fringes of... On the fringes of the city. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh I see, I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A little bit out. It wasn’t way out but is now a suburb. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So it was really only probably three or four miles out of the city and they had a big army camp there.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm... I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: (Says something that cannot be understood)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, how...pa-pa-pa-pa-pa umm. Was it difficult to find food during the war? How did you find...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Food was rationed but we were never really without. We were never really without food like there wasn’t the circumstance where you just couldn’t buy...couldn’t buy meat. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah I get it. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But it was rationed and we were issued with what they called, “ration books” </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ration books?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ration books and the books had little coupons, tiny little coupons in them. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The page..the page was numbered. You know? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and each week, you were allowed or you were allocated so many coupons.  </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhhhh, I see. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If you want to make a note, if you want to make a note of this, the foods that were rationed, correct me if I’m wrong (</em>talking to Nan), <em>the foods that were rationed were meat...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Meat, yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...butter,</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Butter.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...tea,</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Tea. Also tea?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...sugar...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Cinnamon? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I beg your pardon. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What did you say before? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sugar, sugar, just “sugar”. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh “sugar.” Not cinnamon. (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: meat...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Meat, butter, tea, sugar...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...tea, sugar</em><strong>.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Clothing. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, clothing. Okay. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Everyone always had lots of clothing coupons over because they didn’t have the money to buy the clothing. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ah, yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Had surplus. They always had surplus...surplus clothing tickets. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and I still remember, we always ran out of butter...at...like on a Sunday... </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and the new coupons start till Monday. (giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother used to send me ‘round to these people like the (Nan coughing in the background) ahh... At the what we call a “corner store.” We used to call it the “corner store.” </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Like a little convenient store right? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Like a little convenient store down the road from you. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You know that seven-eleven or whatever it is. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, “Family mart.” </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother...my mother would send me around cause the shops...the shops weren’t open everyday...then. B-but in those days, they were open...only open for about an hour late in the afternoon on a Sunday. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So I would go with a note to ask this lady if she could get us half-a-pound of butter in advance against next weeks coupons. (giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (giggle)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: (says something that cannot be understood) Right?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and I would always use... I used to go to the butcher and I will hand the coupon numbers. My mother didn’t know, I used to handle all of that. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: She relied on me to know what the coupon numbers were. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And there were so many coupon numbers for a pound of meat and you know, that sort of thing. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Pop knew what the numbers were. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Smart.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I would have to take the coupons. I used to just take the catalogue, but I didn’t take the book, I don’t think. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (interrupts Pop) How...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: (says something)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: ...about...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...I knew what the coupon series was. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh. H-how about your brothers?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, they didn’t do anything ‘cause I was the eldest so I did that. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh Yeah. Uh-um Pops?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yes?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: So, it was meat, butter, tea, sugar, and clothing right? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Meat, butter, tea, sugar, and clothing, you’re right, that’s it. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: But no like...how ‘bout like flour and stuff?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No they were no rationing of flour, Bernie was there? (Nan says no) No, there were no rationing of flour, or fruit things but biscuits were not available. They were rationed. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So my uncle...my uncle was like a uhh, a department manager at a grocery store in the big grocery store... You know in the city of Rockhampton?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: So it was like uhh like Coles or Woolworths?  </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Uhh yes, a supermarket. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and when you go through, they had the biscuits under the counter, you know, hidden? (Mum laughs in the background)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and he’ll come up to the lady who served on the...like the checkout lady. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, yeah, yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and those days there was no scanning or anything, they just had to push, you know the old cash registers with the buttons? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: One shilling and six pence which was what they just ring that up and he come up and say to the woman on the till to give a packet of biscuits. We had to pay for it, you know, we were allowed to have a a packet of biscuits. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh lucky.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So he sorta, at his discretion. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They were available for everyone. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah so you guys got the secret...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and tin fruit. Tinned fruit, you know what we call “can fruit”? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What kind of fruit?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ah like can peaches and pairs. Can fruit was very scarce. </em>\r\n\r\n<em>  </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What? (Mum says “Sukunai” which means “few” in Japanese) Ohhh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You know, you buy a can of can fruit, don’t you? Or you might get them in bottles now.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I thought Queensland produced like...the amount of fruit...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Can pineapple and all that, yes. But it was all very difficult. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, ok. It was difficult. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t know. I think, I think that the...that sort of industry was perhaps restricted in to some extent. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Can fruit. These things were available but they were difficult, they were rationed. </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were very lucky. You didn’t have to have a coupon but you were very lucky to have one. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: So Pop, so you got your food at like just what do they call it, a supermarket? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was called a corner store. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Corner store...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A corner store. Or yes a supermarket which was called a “Cash and Carry.” C-A-S-H and carry, C-A-R-R-Y. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So you paid cash and carried your good away. (laugh) </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Cash and Carry. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You should be able to access on the computer. They were all called “Cash and Carry.”</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And this was a big store in Rockhampton. And there were only one or two in the main CBD of Rockhampton. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and a man used to ride a bicycle around the suburbs and take your order. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh! Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He would come...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Like a delivery service? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Exactly. He would come and take the order. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother said two pounds, because everything was in pounds and ounces at those days. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and he would come and she would say “two pounds of sugar” and he just knew all the prices off like that. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And he might say we got this going on this week and my mother would order and when she finished the order, he would add up the order and she paid and...he’d take the order away and later in the week, the delivery vehicle would come with the box of groceries and stuff.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That operates...operated all the time. It wasn’t exclusive to the war years. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But the other things about the scares of can fruit, biscuits and all that, ration of food were particularly relevant to the war years.  </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see. What was your favorite food, like type of food during the war, when you were a kid.  </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What made you like excited to have?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were not excited but well yes, we were always thought it was great to get this can fruit. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, can fruit?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: or these cream biscuits. They were delicacy. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and ice-cream because no one, very few people had refrigerators.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: or had what we called ice-chest. C-H-E-S-T. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ice-chest. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and you used to get a big box of ice delivered by the ice man. That kept all the perishable goods fresh.  </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (Accidentally music plays) oops! Oh ok. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The temperature in those ice-chests were never cold enough to...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: preserve? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...or store ice-cream, it will just melt. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, I see. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It’s like a refrigerator. So, we would go to the shop and buy and ice-cream cone. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Was there like an ice-cream man? Like you know the...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I think so, wasn’t there? Ice-cream man? No, no, you just went to the corner store and bought it.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You buy it in a ice-cream cone. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, yum.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...cone, you know?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Was there like vanilla ice-cream? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, maybe. Yeah you can get a penny or a... You can get a small cone for one penny which is a tiny little cone...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...or the standard size, single cone would cost three pence. Was that right Bernie? (Nan says yes.) Three pence which was about two cents. (Mum gasps) </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The other thing that you could buy, if you wanted it what was they used to be call it a “family brick” B-R-I-C-K, which was like a house brick, the size of that or a bit bigger. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So if you were having that as a treat, you will buy that and it was all wrapped up especially in a box. (Nan says “dry ice”) No, we never got it in dry ice. And we would go off and get it in the morning and you know you had to try and stop it from melting and you would cut it in to a...you could cut it in to slices. So you can get ice-cream in a cone, or in a “family brick.”</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, a family brick. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: B-R-I-C-K. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So that was all about at that time. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That was not exclusive to the war years but it was about that time.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That’s how you got ice-cream. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (Mum: I’m listening Dad, I’m on his couch. I’m here in his room.) </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What sort of changes did the war make in your lifestyle at the time? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well I was probably, I was probably too young because I was born just before the war started. I just lived that life and went to school everyday.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah so?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But in those early years, we only went to school everyday but we finished school at 12 o’clock. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wait, everyday which includes...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Everyday. A half day. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: But does that include Saturdays and Sundays?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, we never went on Saturday or Sunday. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And I don’t know whenever...I just don’t know why that was so. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh so, it’s not because of the war? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t know the reason for that, but that was in the catholic school but the state...public school...or state school had the class went for two and a half days. Two full days and the other half went for the remaining two and a half days. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I just don’t know why. What was your experience, Bernie? Did you have that? ...No Nan can’ remember that. But I distinctly remember.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, we had a fairly normal life. But we had to blacken the windows, that was something. That was the only thing. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Blacken the windows? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Blacken. B-L-A-C-K-E-N. Darken. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: How? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We had this a...a gray...like a...what would you call it...not felt...it’s like a gray cardboard-y soft cardboard. Gray soft cardboard. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...which had to be nailed. The windows were all wood in those days and not like your place, metal. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was timber windows. Like a gray, light cardboard, but you could tear it. It had to be nailed over the windows with all these little tacks. So at night time, when you put the lights on,</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? It won’t be seen from outside right?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...no one could see outside. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If there was a airway attack at night, the enemy would not be able to see.</em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...the house, you with me?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yes.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And they used to have local people going around as what they called, “air raid wardens.” Air raid wardens. W-A-R-D-E-N-S. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Air raid wardens. (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Air raid wardens. So they would go around checking the area. You know, I don’t know how big of an area they had. But this man, he only lived about ohh...down our street. He knocked on our door one night to tell Nanna Balaam that he could see light through one of the windows. (giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh (Mum laughs)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If they see light, they will knock on your door so you will have to darken your house. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Ohhh. (laugh)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: How did I remember that...ha!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Funny!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) Wow.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Hmm.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Do you have any particular...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Other from that...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Other than that, to me it was just a normal life-style. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, ok. Normal life-style. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I do remember, like my mother and other women talking and they were sort of very concerned and frightened...and frightened the prospects of being invaded. You know? I mean I was a kid...as a kid I just remember that cause adults. We wouldn’t. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: At six or seven you wouldn’t be taking in all...but I do remember these women talking and being very I said afraid at the prospects of a...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Invasion?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...invasion. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: By the Japanese?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well yes, with all due respect. Japanese invasion. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Because the Germans weren’t going to invade. Too far. Japanese invasion and how would they be treated. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hm, um, um. (agreed)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I do remember my mother talking to these ladies once or twice. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Once only, really. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I can’t believe you still believe it Pops. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sorry?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I can’t believe you still remember it. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yes, I do. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Yeah, you have a good memory.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: You have a great memory! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well, I wouldn’t have remember what happened two weeks ago. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: A good long-term memory but a bad short-term memory.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well, I distinctly remember this. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I didn\'t make that up! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: No. I know. You are a good interviewee.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yes, thank you! Do you have any particular happy memories from war time? If so, would you like to share one with me?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Did the teacher wrote these? (whispers)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yes. (whispers)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well, no...uhh...yes. They were happy times because periodically, my father...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, oh came back from...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, who you never knew...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: he’d be allowed to come home on leave. (Says something that cannot be understood)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Came back how many times? I’m sorry, when? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He would come home on leave. Just for a couple of days. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Leave?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Leave. L-E-A-V-E\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: </em>L-E-A-V-E. We say, “come home on leave.”\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh. Was it also like...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He’d be given time off the work.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. (typing) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ahhh. So, he’d come home. It might just be for a couple of days and I don’t think he was ever home for a week. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He was home for short periods. I don’t know for specific. He was home for short periods. </em>\r\n\r\n<em>. </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: How about like Christmas and stuff? Or like Easter?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No...not for specific. I can’t remember that. I...from my point of view, I always had Christmas school holidays out at my aunts. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. Christmas, school holidays... (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Your mother will remember. Aunt Stella. My Aunt Stella. S-T-E-L-L-A. Well just my aunt. I always had Christmas with her with a Christmas tree. But that was all the time. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I was ten, eleven, or twelve. It wasn’t confined to war years only. It was Christmas with her, I probably never had Christmas at home at all. I was always out at my aunties! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Where...where is your aunts? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh, she lived a suburb called Frenchville. F-R-E-N-C-H-V-I-L-L-E. Frenchville, which was those days, she lived about 2 miles up from the suburban area, up a bush road... It was in the bush. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Pass of Frenchville, cause they had the state school and everything there. Pass of Frenchville, well like suburban but it was getting into the outer suburbs. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Two miles further up this single gravel road. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So if you were singing along and you heard a car coming, you had to get off the road and go in the bush so that the car can pass. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was a single road. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Made out of gravel. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well that is not particular to the war years only. </em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah that is just when you are...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...getting back to the can fruit, she had this big stock up of can fruit...(giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Woah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Woah.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: She must have bought it before the war, during the war. (giggle) She used to have it hidden downstairs in a big cupboard. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) Did you steal...?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And every Sunday...I can still see this big box, it was a bog box. Tilt on its side. A big crate with a shelf and she had a piece of heshen, like a bag...heshen bag in front of it. H-E-S-H-E-N.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...that hid all the can goods she had. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and every Sunday, I’ll go down and bring back a, cause it had a high house, I’ll bring up a can of fruit and we would have that for our Sunday dessert! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Hahahaha.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh yeah? (laugh) Yum. (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: We take things for granted.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, how about a sad memory? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...oh. (pause) Well, not particularly of the war. I never had...I didn’t have any...no, I didn’t have any family members, or uncles or aunts because they were all...they were people who...oh yes, I did have an uncle! In World War II and he served in New Guinea but he came home safely. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So we didn’t have anyone wounded or killed like you hear about the different stories about the people on the Berber railway or...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I never knew anyone like that...ahh...the only...the only sad thing I could remember is this a...she would be a young woman in those days, maybe...maybe not even 20. I’m trying to think and she was going out with this American soldier. I don’t think she became engaged with him but she was going out with him and very fond of him and he was killed in the war. </em>\r\n\r\n<em>  </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...So I do remember that. She was Jean’s elder sister.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, that’s sad.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t remember whether she became engaged. I can’t remember. Anyhow, he was killed and she met someone else and got married and had a family. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yes, I remember that. That was sad. Because I have actually met this man. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and his name was Hank. H-A-N-K. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh! Hank...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Shane’s dog...\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. Do you remember seeing soldiers during the war? What countries did these soldiers come from? You’ve seen Americans soldiers. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...One day, a convoy of soldiers were passing through this suburb on Park Ave. where  I lived.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Convoy?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A convoy of soldiers, in the trucks. Like you see in these movies. You know, going through Germany in those war movies. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: In those trucks. Well, they were going in the backs of trucks like that. Ahh through this suburb. Down on the main street. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and I was on the footpath. I don’t know whether it was lunch time or I might have been coming home. I used to go home for my lunch because I used to live so close to the school. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I will go home for the main lunch. We rarely really took our lunch. We went home, most times. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Anyhow, they threw pennies to all the...they threw pennies, a whole hand full of pennies. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A penny would only be..equal to...be less than a cent. Right Bernie? A penny would be less than a cent. So they threw pennies and I think I managed to pick one up off the footpath. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Some kids got more than I did. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They scattered through. They threw pennies to us kids. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh. That’s nice. How about...what else? Only pennies? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...Yeah. I just only remember them giving pennies. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...hand full of pennies.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh. So, it was only American soldiers? No like British soldiers? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We didn’t see the British or any other Europeans. Because the British were all in Europe. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ah yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...or North Africa or whatever. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The only foreign troops that we ever had in Australia to my knowledge...and you could be able to confirm it, were the Americans. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok. Umm, the question is, “did you witness...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I’m sorry, did you witness what?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: “Did you witness any battles or violence?” But you haven’t right?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, no sorry. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It’s ok. (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, I have never witness anybody but I think they used to be, when you read about this, there were a certain amount of... And certainly in Brisbane...not up in Rockhampton...there were a certain amount of ill-feelings between the Australian and American troops.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What’s that?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sorry, you’re right?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: ...Ill-feelings? What? Sorry.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ill-feelings. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Bad feeling.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The Australians didn’t think too highly of the Americans...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhhh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The term is “ill-feelings” Meaning that they didn’t feel well...you know...because of all the young women were going out with the American soldiers. (giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: (laugh)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And you know, the Australians...they more had to take second place! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hahaha. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The Americans were, you know, entertaining the Australian women. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh..</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I mean I wasn’t exposed to that because I was a six, seven, or eight year old kid. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That wasn’t about me.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You know, I heard about that later.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh. I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So that’s not directly relevant. So the answer to that question is no. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I didn’t witness anything.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Are there any other stories from this time period that you would like to share with me? Anything else!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...No. I’m trying to think... Ahh. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Dad, did you tell Jack the reason why you don’t like sweet potato now?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh yeah! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh no. That does not have to do with the war. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That does not have to do with the war. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Ok, sorry.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, I’ll tell you that afterwards. I’m trying to think, the only thing I remember is one time, there was a well-known pilot, and he was flying this plane...I don’t know what kind of aircraft. But it was called G for George. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: G for George. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was well known. And he was a well known pilot. So he flew over Rockhampton. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (typing) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And he were out, just looking at this plane as it flew over. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and I mean really, if you Google, “G for George”, on the computer, you would probably find out about the story behind it. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t know.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I will look it up. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Was it called “G” or called “G for George”?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It’s called, “G for George”!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: (laugh)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: G for George!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, G for George!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: G for George. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: That’s cool.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, it’s not just called “G”. It’s called “G for George”!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Google, “G for George” and see what comes up!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, I will. I will google it. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It will be interesting because he was a well-known pilot at Park Ave. where we saw. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: G for George...I think I found it already! Wow. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Have you?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, G for George. Ok, it’s a...let’s see....I will read it. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Can you Google it while talking to me?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. Ok, “G for George flew 90 operational missions over Germany and occupied Europe during the height of the bomber offensive. From the time it was built in 1942 until its retirement from active service in 1944, the bomber was flown by Number 460 Squadron...” </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Squadron.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, squadron. R-A-A-F. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: R double A F which stand for the Royal Australian Air Force. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...(cannot be understood)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: A beg your pardon?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Does it say that it was particularly flown by any pilot? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, let’s see. Pilot... Um, Alec Saintsmith. Alec Saintsmith. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, the name doesn’t mean anything. But there, that’s it aircraft, it flew over! (giggles)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Wow! Ha!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Do you remember it Dad? Remember seeing it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yes! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: There is a photo with the Australian Prime Minister, Mr. Curtin?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Curtin. C-U-R-T-I-N. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh no. Harry Tickle. No I don’t know, he is the Grand Staff Engineer, responsible for the main...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Maintenance.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah...maintenance, for the bomber, G for George. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: There! I remembered something correctly!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I thought it might have been one, but it could be different pilots. That plane definitely flew over. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It was all over Germany right?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...so it must of made..come home to Australia and then because it was such a you know, well-known aircraft. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Today it is displayed in the Anzac Hall at the Australia War Memorial in Canberra. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh, is it? I would have to remember that!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I would have to go and see it.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Right, that was my little trip about that! G for George.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, thank you! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: What else do you want to ask?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Is there anything that you would like to tell the younger generations about your experience WW2 or about war in general?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well, I don’t have any...well I was a kid, you know...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You have asked me before...I forgot...I’ll answer this question now. No, I don’t particularly remember...anything that I sorta wanna pass on...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...as a child. My experiences were really normal and broad except that you know, things were a bit rationed but we were never hungry. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were never hungry, we just had to ration...and the good that we had were simple. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But then, yes, war in general...well, yes. War in general is...is just...how can I put it? It should not be contemplated. Just look at the war in Afghanistan, and the war in Iraq. And people are...you know....people have been...you know....people have been sent to war and the senseless slaughter and the loss of lives. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and on all sides. So, there is no reason for war. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...except if someone invaded a country, well then the people who are living there quite entitle to do something...to parts...bits of their country. To go off with you know whats the word...oh...to declare war on someone...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Self-defense isn’t it?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well I said in defense. There is no, yes, reason really...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam:...for war cause you know, just so many, so many innocent people and even the troops are killed and just look at it. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We just had Anzac Day which reminded us...reminds us of the senseless war....organized or determined by the British officers. They did not have much idea what they were doing quite frankly. People were just sent...as we say, lands to the slaughter. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: There is no real...no real...no reason for war. Things have to be resolved without war but as I said, the only thing is ahh...naturally, a country is invaded. Those people are entitled to try to defend themselves. They can’t just sit there and let the invader take their land. You know?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. I know what you mean. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The one you asked me before, you alright with that one?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A happy moment did you say, did you ask me some question about that somewhere along the...?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, I asked you, “What’s was one of the...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...happy memories. I remember when peace in the pacific was declared. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, when...(typing)...so that was August 15...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The war end on August 15, 1945. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, August 15, 1945. That is when the Japanese emperor spoke to the...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I remember that because, this lad...who lived around the corner in the next street, he was older than I am, rode a bicycle down our street...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...towing an empty kerosene can which was like a...would hold a... Four gallons, do you have things in gallons or liters over there in Japan?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Liters.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong><em>Brian Balaam: Liters. So, there was about...how many liters are in a gallon? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I will calculate it right now. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Roughly, roughly.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Three is it?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Four or something. Is it?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It’s ok...one liter is 0.26417 US gallons. Ok, wait, gallons to liters right? (door bell ringing) Ok Pops, it is 3.7 liters.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Isn’t it 3?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: 3.8 actually. 3.8 liters. (doorbell ringing again)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: one...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: One gallon is 3.8 liters. Roughly. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So in other words, the kerosene...so he was towing an empty 15 liter...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...on his bicycle. Just to make a noise...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...to celebrate that peace has arrived. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: So...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: This boy rode his bike down our street...a gravel street. So this empty kerosene drum which was a square, it was a square in those days which was big enough to carry 15~16 liters, it was bouncing off the back of his bike and this other younger lad was running behind him and we put up strings of paper flags. Those days, you couldn’t even get a flag, the Australian flag. You couldn’t get a flag during the war years made out of material.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So they were all paper flags. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, paper flags. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, made out of paper, you know?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So there were little paper flags in front of our house in Rockhampton on the front verandah between two posts flying...well they were just hanging like a banner, to celebrate peace. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So...I don’t think you are aware of it, originally, that date of August was called, “VJ Day” which stood for “Victory over Japan” </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: VJ Day.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: VJ Day, Victory over Japan. But more recent years, it was changed to try and be more sensitive to the Japanese, they changed it to VP Day which is Victory over the Pacific. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You with me?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. So Victory to Japan Day to Victory in the Pacific Day. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Victory over the Pacific, yes.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The other one is called the VE Day which is Victory in...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Europe!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...which would some time in was it in May?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yes, May. Let’s see. V...(Googling “VE Day”)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Did your mother get went to get the door?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. VE Day is um May 8th. But in Commonwealth countries it is May 7th. Why, I don’t know why. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We remember this as students at that time, students of a Catholic school, we always thought it was just one of those unusual things that victory in the Pacific was declared on the feast of the Assumption. The Assumption</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Feast of the Assumption. And you could look up the calendar in May, interesting, Europe was declared on the feast of the Assumption. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh so it’s...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You look it up!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A-S-S-U-M-P-T-I-O-N. </em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, victory...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So, victory in Europe was declared on the feast of the Assumption. Thereabouts. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, let’s see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The feast of the Assumptions...you know the nuns made a point of this at our Catholic school. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, haha.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I still remember that! I might be wrong, well I would have to access a Catholic calendar which you probably could. 1945 to find out when the feast of the Assumption was. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Let’s see. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Call that out. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Catholic calendar. Let’s see...I got a Catholic calendar. Catholic calendar...is it the Roman Catholic Saints...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: What?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Um... </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That will do. The Roman Catholic calendar... </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, let’s see. July...Feast in the...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: 1945 you gotta get cause the feast changes each year.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. Feast...1945. (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Noe you gotta get the Feast of the Assumption. A-S-S-U-M-P-T-I-O-N. Which date was it? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: 8th of July...wait...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, it’s not July...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wait, what are we trying to find again?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The Feast of the Assumption. A-S-S-P</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: -T-I-O-N. In 1945. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (typing) Ok, the Feast of the Assumption, 1945. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: What date?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It was...um...(pause) I can’t find it...May 20!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh, is it?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Something like that...yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh..well, we are wrong then. We were always told that is was close to the Feast of the Assumption. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wait, in 1945...um um um...yeah that’s it.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If you could look up Easter. When was Easter in 1945?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, Easter in 1945. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The Assumption is 40 days after Easter. I can work it out then. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, Easter 1945...was April 1st. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: April 1st?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup. Which means, it was the 21st? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sorry?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: In 1945, Easter Day was April the 1st. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Alright, so that is 30. There, that is 38 days. We are saying the Feast of the Assumption but it was close to it.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were always told that.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So that is what they saying, the...did they say the victory was the 8th of May? Was it? 1945.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, and I think that is when the kamikaze attacked...wait the kamikaze (Googling “kamikaze attacks”) You know Pops, when you were living Rockhampton, did you hear anything about what happened in...Darwin?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ahh...I don’t remember that.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: How many people died in Darwin? Let’s see...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, I don’t know. I can’t remember that, Jack. Sorry. (Skype sound)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Darwin...Japanese...attack (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I think there were 100 0r something. Weren\'t there? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: The bombing of Darwin. It was on February 19th, 1942. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, I don’t think...I think it was kept fairly quiet.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: “It was the first and the largest single attack by a foreign power against Australia.” </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That’s right.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, there were 240 Japanese aircraft attacked ships in Darwin’s harbor and umm...let’s see...how many people died?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was over 100 I think. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: 250~320 killed.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh, my goodness. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: ...and ten ships were sunk, 23 aircrafts destroyed...yeah. So, that’s it. That’s sad.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: How many ships sunk? How many ships were sunk?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh...ten. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Goodness.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: And 20 damaged. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They just celebrated...commemorated, not celebrated...the 70th anniversary, you see...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, really?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: In Darwin. Oh, yes. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Do they do that every year?</strong>\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: No, 70 years.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, yeah it is 70 years!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: It was 42 and now it is 2012 so...\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They may have an annual commemoration but this year was the 70th. And I don\'t remember hearing anything and I think the federal government kept it quiet so not to panic the people. I think you may find that, but I’m not sure. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, thank you!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My iPad is down to 17%, I have to go charge it. How is it going?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It’s good, it’s good. I just finished! Well, thank you for your time!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I’m not trying to get rid of you but I just looked up...I’m down to 16%, we would have to recharge. </em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, you should. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Is it ok? You asked everything?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You sure?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Very interesting Dad! (claps)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Thank you very much! (claps)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That’s alright!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Hurray!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Thank you Pops! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Hurray!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Thank you for your time! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', '', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1877-revision-3', '', '', '2012-05-28 09:56:10', '2012-05-28 13:56:10', '', 1877, 'http://localhost:8888/benmerde2012/2012/05/1877-revision-3/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ;
INSERT INTO `wp_lhejar_posts` ( `ID`, `post_author`, `post_date`, `post_date_gmt`, `post_content`, `post_title`, `post_category`, `post_excerpt`, `post_status`, `comment_status`, `ping_status`, `post_password`, `post_name`, `to_ping`, `pinged`, `post_modified`, `post_modified_gmt`, `post_content_filtered`, `post_parent`, `guid`, `menu_order`, `post_type`, `post_mime_type`, `comment_count`) VALUES
(1881, 1, '2012-05-28 09:56:18', '2012-05-28 13:56:18', '<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah I can hear you.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi:<strong> </strong>Record it, Jack.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah I pressed start. It’s recording. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Alright.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay Pops. Uhhh... (pause) Basic interview scrip...Interview must be 45 minutes longer. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Go on. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, where were you living during World War II? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Rockhampton, Central Queensland, Australia. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: R-O-C-K...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Haha I know Poppy.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: (Laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: *Laugh* Wait, Wasn’t Rockhampton the second largest city in Queensland at that time?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Possibly, that’s right. It was at one time. Yes, possibly. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Well...umm...what’s there...what’s famous there?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They...they refer to it as today the beef capital of Australia so there was a lot of beef... Beef cattle industry. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh I see... I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But more in the inland and the surrounding districts, I should think.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm... How old were you at the time?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ahh... </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I mean when it began... It began in 1941 right? Or something like that...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, World War II in Europe commenced in 1939...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, in 1939. Okay...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and I would have been three in the November.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay so three...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I was only two when the war started. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay... How about when it ended? August 1945.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: August 1945... So I was eight! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Eight when it ended? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Correct. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay. Wait, Pops, how old are you right now? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I am seventy-five! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: You are seventy-five now... Okay. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Correct. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, alright. Umm... Who were you living with? ...at the time. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother and two brothers. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh yeah yeah, </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother and two brothers. That’s Nanna Balaam. You remember her. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah... </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So with my mother and two brothers who were younger than I am. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wait, wher...how about your dad? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He was not away in the war, but he was uhh... the word was I suppose... conscripted because he was a cabinet maker...he had to built accommodation for the American troops...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh... Where was he sent... Where did they send him?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Townsville, North Queensland</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Towns...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He was in Townsville, North Queensland...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh okay...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And Brisbane, I think. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh really?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Brisbane at some time...yes... Yes he was. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Was he, Bernie? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong><em>Bernice Balaam (Nan): Yes, he was. </em></strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He was in Townsville and Brisbane. At the best of my knowledge. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, what was your occupation?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Who’s occupation?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Your occupation.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I was a school boy at that point. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: School student ... (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Is that what you mean? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, which school did you attend?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...school boy.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Which school did you attend?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: St. Joseph’s Convent School </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: St. Joseph’s Convent School... (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: St. Joseph’s Convent School... </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Is it still here? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The school is still there but there are no more nuns there...anymore.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, so what is it know? It’s not a Catholic school anymore?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah but it’s staffed by lay people.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh I see...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It is still a Catholic school but there aren’t any nuns. You know, there are a few nuns around but its...still a Catholic school at the same site. S-I-T-E. Same site. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see. Um...so what grade were you in? What...like...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I came in school at the beginning of 1942</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: 1942...okay.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I began school in 1942.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: How was...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And they weren’t called “grades”, they were called “preps.” P-R-E-P-S. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, preps. Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Short for “preparatory.” </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, preps. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We had two preps in a year. At that year I was in prep 1 and after six months you went into prep 2.</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh really?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Then the next year you will be in prep 3 and then prep 4. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Then you went into grade 1.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhhhh. So is it kinda like kindergarden? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...No, no. You learnt things. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahhh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were learning the alphabet. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: K, and like 1+1? Addition and stuff?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ohh, vaguely. Things like “A for apple, B for bat”, you know, that sort of thing. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: C... I forget what C was for. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Did you guys learn about the war? Or did you...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sorry?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Did you guys know like...did the teachers talk about the war and stuff?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No. I wouldn’t say. I don’t remember the teachers talking about the war but we had...we had airway practice everyday.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What is that?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Airway practice at about 12 o’clock. Well, it was to prepare us in the event of enemy planes coming over with the intention of dropping bombs. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh. Everyday?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Everyday at 12 o’clock...well regularly, it might be everyday. I still remember it. And the nun who was in charge...a sister who was in charge stood... *laugh* you know at the top of the staircase, blow the whistle, and all us kids will race down the stairs like that...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Jump into these open trenches, which were dug in the school grounds.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If a plane ever came and dropped a bomb, and landed on us, that will be it. I wouldn’t be here today. *laugh*</em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) But, luckily did the..No enemy planes...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, Rockhampton. Rockhampton didn’t...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: But like...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Rockhampton: ...was never a subject to any enemy...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Only like Darwin right?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, that is correct. But we were practicing in case. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, I see. Well, the Ame-Americans were actually in Queensland as well?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They were. They were at a place called Parkhurst. P-A-R-K-H-U-R-S-T. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Which was... It’s now a suburb of Rockhampton but in those days, it was like a... On the fringes of... On the fringes of the city. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh I see, I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A little bit out. It wasn’t way out but is now a suburb. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So it was really only probably three or four miles out of the city and they had a big army camp there.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm... I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: (Says something that cannot be understood)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, how...pa-pa-pa-pa-pa umm. Was it difficult to find food during the war? How did you find...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Food was rationed but we were never really without. We were never really without food like there wasn’t the circumstance where you just couldn’t buy...couldn’t buy meat. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah I get it. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But it was rationed and we were issued with what they called, “ration books” </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ration books?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ration books and the books had little coupons, tiny little coupons in them. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The page..the page was numbered. You know? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and each week, you were allowed or you were allocated so many coupons.  </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhhhh, I see. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If you want to make a note, if you want to make a note of this, the foods that were rationed, correct me if I’m wrong (</em>talking to Nan), <em>the foods that were rationed were meat...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Meat, yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...butter,</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Butter.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...tea,</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Tea. Also tea?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...sugar...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Cinnamon? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I beg your pardon. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What did you say before? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sugar, sugar, just “sugar”. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh “sugar.” Not cinnamon. (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: meat...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Meat, butter, tea, sugar...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...tea, sugar</em><strong>.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Clothing. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, clothing. Okay. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Everyone always had lots of clothing coupons over because they didn’t have the money to buy the clothing. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ah, yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Had surplus. They always had surplus...surplus clothing tickets. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and I still remember, we always ran out of butter...at...like on a Sunday... </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and the new coupons start till Monday. (giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother used to send me ‘round to these people like the (Nan coughing in the background) ahh... At the what we call a “corner store.” We used to call it the “corner store.” </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Like a little convenient store right? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Like a little convenient store down the road from you. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You know that seven-eleven or whatever it is. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, “Family mart.” </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother...my mother would send me around cause the shops...the shops weren’t open everyday...then. B-but in those days, they were open...only open for about an hour late in the afternoon on a Sunday. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So I would go with a note to ask this lady if she could get us half-a-pound of butter in advance against next weeks coupons. (giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (giggle)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: (says something that cannot be understood) Right?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and I would always use... I used to go to the butcher and I will hand the coupon numbers. My mother didn’t know, I used to handle all of that. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: She relied on me to know what the coupon numbers were. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And there were so many coupon numbers for a pound of meat and you know, that sort of thing. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Pop knew what the numbers were. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Smart.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I would have to take the coupons. I used to just take the catalogue, but I didn’t take the book, I don’t think. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (interrupts Pop) How...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: (says something)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: ...about...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...I knew what the coupon series was. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh. H-how about your brothers?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, they didn’t do anything ‘cause I was the eldest so I did that. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh Yeah. Uh-um Pops?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yes?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: So, it was meat, butter, tea, sugar, and clothing right? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Meat, butter, tea, sugar, and clothing, you’re right, that’s it. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: But no like...how ‘bout like flour and stuff?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No they were no rationing of flour, Bernie was there? (Nan says no) No, there were no rationing of flour, or fruit things but biscuits were not available. They were rationed. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So my uncle...my uncle was like a uhh, a department manager at a grocery store in the big grocery store... You know in the city of Rockhampton?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: So it was like uhh like Coles or Woolworths?  </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Uhh yes, a supermarket. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and when you go through, they had the biscuits under the counter, you know, hidden? (Mum laughs in the background)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and he’ll come up to the lady who served on the...like the checkout lady. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, yeah, yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and those days there was no scanning or anything, they just had to push, you know the old cash registers with the buttons? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: One shilling and six pence which was what they just ring that up and he come up and say to the woman on the till to give a packet of biscuits. We had to pay for it, you know, we were allowed to have a a packet of biscuits. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh lucky.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So he sorta, at his discretion. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They were available for everyone. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah so you guys got the secret...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and tin fruit. Tinned fruit, you know what we call “can fruit”? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What kind of fruit?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ah like can peaches and pairs. Can fruit was very scarce. </em>\r\n\r\n<em>  </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What? (Mum says “Sukunai” which means “few” in Japanese) Ohhh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You know, you buy a can of can fruit, don’t you? Or you might get them in bottles now.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I thought Queensland produced like...the amount of fruit...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Can pineapple and all that, yes. But it was all very difficult. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, ok. It was difficult. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t know. I think, I think that the...that sort of industry was perhaps restricted in to some extent. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Can fruit. These things were available but they were difficult, they were rationed. </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were very lucky. You didn’t have to have a coupon but you were very lucky to have one. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: So Pop, so you got your food at like just what do they call it, a supermarket? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was called a corner store. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Corner store...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A corner store. Or yes a supermarket which was called a “Cash and Carry.” C-A-S-H and carry, C-A-R-R-Y. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So you paid cash and carried your good away. (laugh) </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Cash and Carry. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You should be able to access on the computer. They were all called “Cash and Carry.”</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And this was a big store in Rockhampton. And there were only one or two in the main CBD of Rockhampton. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and a man used to ride a bicycle around the suburbs and take your order. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh! Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He would come...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Like a delivery service? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Exactly. He would come and take the order. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My mother said two pounds, because everything was in pounds and ounces at those days. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and he would come and she would say “two pounds of sugar” and he just knew all the prices off like that. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And he might say we got this going on this week and my mother would order and when she finished the order, he would add up the order and she paid and...he’d take the order away and later in the week, the delivery vehicle would come with the box of groceries and stuff.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That operates...operated all the time. It wasn’t exclusive to the war years. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But the other things about the scares of can fruit, biscuits and all that, ration of food were particularly relevant to the war years.  </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see. What was your favorite food, like type of food during the war, when you were a kid.  </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What made you like excited to have?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were not excited but well yes, we were always thought it was great to get this can fruit. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, can fruit?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: or these cream biscuits. They were delicacy. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and ice-cream because no one, very few people had refrigerators.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: or had what we called ice-chest. C-H-E-S-T. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ice-chest. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and you used to get a big box of ice delivered by the ice man. That kept all the perishable goods fresh.  </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (Accidentally music plays) oops! Oh ok. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The temperature in those ice-chests were never cold enough to...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: preserve? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...or store ice-cream, it will just melt. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, I see. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It’s like a refrigerator. So, we would go to the shop and buy and ice-cream cone. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Was there like an ice-cream man? Like you know the...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I think so, wasn’t there? Ice-cream man? No, no, you just went to the corner store and bought it.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You buy it in a ice-cream cone. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, yum.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...cone, you know?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Was there like vanilla ice-cream? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, maybe. Yeah you can get a penny or a... You can get a small cone for one penny which is a tiny little cone...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...or the standard size, single cone would cost three pence. Was that right Bernie? (Nan says yes.) Three pence which was about two cents. (Mum gasps) </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The other thing that you could buy, if you wanted it what was they used to be call it a “family brick” B-R-I-C-K, which was like a house brick, the size of that or a bit bigger. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So if you were having that as a treat, you will buy that and it was all wrapped up especially in a box. (Nan says “dry ice”) No, we never got it in dry ice. And we would go off and get it in the morning and you know you had to try and stop it from melting and you would cut it in to a...you could cut it in to slices. So you can get ice-cream in a cone, or in a “family brick.”</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, a family brick. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: B-R-I-C-K. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So that was all about at that time. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That was not exclusive to the war years but it was about that time.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That’s how you got ice-cream. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (Mum: I’m listening Dad, I’m on his couch. I’m here in his room.) </strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What sort of changes did the war make in your lifestyle at the time? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well I was probably, I was probably too young because I was born just before the war started. I just lived that life and went to school everyday.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah so?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But in those early years, we only went to school everyday but we finished school at 12 o’clock. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wait, everyday which includes...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Everyday. A half day. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: But does that include Saturdays and Sundays?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, we never went on Saturday or Sunday. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And I don’t know whenever...I just don’t know why that was so. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh so, it’s not because of the war? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t know the reason for that, but that was in the catholic school but the state...public school...or state school had the class went for two and a half days. Two full days and the other half went for the remaining two and a half days. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I just don’t know why. What was your experience, Bernie? Did you have that? ...No Nan can’ remember that. But I distinctly remember.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, we had a fairly normal life. But we had to blacken the windows, that was something. That was the only thing. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Blacken the windows? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Blacken. B-L-A-C-K-E-N. Darken. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: How? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We had this a...a gray...like a...what would you call it...not felt...it’s like a gray cardboard-y soft cardboard. Gray soft cardboard. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...which had to be nailed. The windows were all wood in those days and not like your place, metal. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was timber windows. Like a gray, light cardboard, but you could tear it. It had to be nailed over the windows with all these little tacks. So at night time, when you put the lights on,</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? It won’t be seen from outside right?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...no one could see outside. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If there was a airway attack at night, the enemy would not be able to see.</em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...the house, you with me?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yes.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And they used to have local people going around as what they called, “air raid wardens.” Air raid wardens. W-A-R-D-E-N-S. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Air raid wardens. (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Air raid wardens. So they would go around checking the area. You know, I don’t know how big of an area they had. But this man, he only lived about ohh...down our street. He knocked on our door one night to tell Nanna Balaam that he could see light through one of the windows. (giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh (Mum laughs)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If they see light, they will knock on your door so you will have to darken your house. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Ohhh. (laugh)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: How did I remember that...ha!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Funny!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) Wow.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Hmm.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Do you have any particular...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Other from that...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Other than that, to me it was just a normal life-style. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, ok. Normal life-style. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I do remember, like my mother and other women talking and they were sort of very concerned and frightened...and frightened the prospects of being invaded. You know? I mean I was a kid...as a kid I just remember that cause adults. We wouldn’t. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: At six or seven you wouldn’t be taking in all...but I do remember these women talking and being very I said afraid at the prospects of a...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Invasion?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...invasion. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: By the Japanese?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well yes, with all due respect. Japanese invasion. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Because the Germans weren’t going to invade. Too far. Japanese invasion and how would they be treated. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hm, um, um. (agreed)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I do remember my mother talking to these ladies once or twice. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Once only, really. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I can’t believe you still believe it Pops. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sorry?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I can’t believe you still remember it. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yes, I do. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Yeah, you have a good memory.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: You have a great memory! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well, I wouldn’t have remember what happened two weeks ago. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: A good long-term memory but a bad short-term memory.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well, I distinctly remember this. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I didn\'t make that up! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: No. I know. You are a good interviewee.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yes, thank you! Do you have any particular happy memories from war time? If so, would you like to share one with me?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Did the teacher wrote these? (whispers)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yes. (whispers)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well, no...uhh...yes. They were happy times because periodically, my father...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, oh came back from...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, who you never knew...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: he’d be allowed to come home on leave. (Says something that cannot be understood)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Came back how many times? I’m sorry, when? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He would come home on leave. Just for a couple of days. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Leave?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Leave. L-E-A-V-E\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: </em>L-E-A-V-E. We say, “come home on leave.”\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh. Was it also like...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He’d be given time off the work.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. (typing) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ahhh. So, he’d come home. It might just be for a couple of days and I don’t think he was ever home for a week. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: He was home for short periods. I don’t know for specific. He was home for short periods. </em>\r\n\r\n<em>. </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: How about like Christmas and stuff? Or like Easter?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No...not for specific. I can’t remember that. I...from my point of view, I always had Christmas school holidays out at my aunts. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. Christmas, school holidays... (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Your mother will remember. Aunt Stella. My Aunt Stella. S-T-E-L-L-A. Well just my aunt. I always had Christmas with her with a Christmas tree. But that was all the time. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I was ten, eleven, or twelve. It wasn’t confined to war years only. It was Christmas with her, I probably never had Christmas at home at all. I was always out at my aunties! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Where...where is your aunts? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh, she lived a suburb called Frenchville. F-R-E-N-C-H-V-I-L-L-E. Frenchville, which was those days, she lived about 2 miles up from the suburban area, up a bush road... It was in the bush. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Pass of Frenchville, cause they had the state school and everything there. Pass of Frenchville, well like suburban but it was getting into the outer suburbs. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Two miles further up this single gravel road. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So if you were singing along and you heard a car coming, you had to get off the road and go in the bush so that the car can pass. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was a single road. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Made out of gravel. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well that is not particular to the war years only. </em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah that is just when you are...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...getting back to the can fruit, she had this big stock up of can fruit...(giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Woah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Woah.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: She must have bought it before the war, during the war. (giggle) She used to have it hidden downstairs in a big cupboard. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh) Did you steal...?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And every Sunday...I can still see this big box, it was a bog box. Tilt on its side. A big crate with a shelf and she had a piece of heshen, like a bag...heshen bag in front of it. H-E-S-H-E-N.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...that hid all the can goods she had. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and every Sunday, I’ll go down and bring back a, cause it had a high house, I’ll bring up a can of fruit and we would have that for our Sunday dessert! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Hahahaha.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh yeah? (laugh) Yum. (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: We take things for granted.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Okay, how about a sad memory? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...oh. (pause) Well, not particularly of the war. I never had...I didn’t have any...no, I didn’t have any family members, or uncles or aunts because they were all...they were people who...oh yes, I did have an uncle! In World War II and he served in New Guinea but he came home safely. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So we didn’t have anyone wounded or killed like you hear about the different stories about the people on the Berber railway or...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I never knew anyone like that...ahh...the only...the only sad thing I could remember is this a...she would be a young woman in those days, maybe...maybe not even 20. I’m trying to think and she was going out with this American soldier. I don’t think she became engaged with him but she was going out with him and very fond of him and he was killed in the war. </em>\r\n\r\n<em>  </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...So I do remember that. She was Jean’s elder sister.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, that’s sad.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t remember whether she became engaged. I can’t remember. Anyhow, he was killed and she met someone else and got married and had a family. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yes, I remember that. That was sad. Because I have actually met this man. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: and his name was Hank. H-A-N-K. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh! Hank...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Shane’s dog...\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. Do you remember seeing soldiers during the war? What countries did these soldiers come from? You’ve seen Americans soldiers. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...One day, a convoy of soldiers were passing through this suburb on Park Ave. where  I lived.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Convoy?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A convoy of soldiers, in the trucks. Like you see in these movies. You know, going through Germany in those war movies. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: In those trucks. Well, they were going in the backs of trucks like that. Ahh through this suburb. Down on the main street. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and I was on the footpath. I don’t know whether it was lunch time or I might have been coming home. I used to go home for my lunch because I used to live so close to the school. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I will go home for the main lunch. We rarely really took our lunch. We went home, most times. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Anyhow, they threw pennies to all the...they threw pennies, a whole hand full of pennies. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah? (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A penny would only be..equal to...be less than a cent. Right Bernie? A penny would be less than a cent. So they threw pennies and I think I managed to pick one up off the footpath. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Some kids got more than I did. (laugh)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They scattered through. They threw pennies to us kids. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh. That’s nice. How about...what else? Only pennies? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...Yeah. I just only remember them giving pennies. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...hand full of pennies.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh. So, it was only American soldiers? No like British soldiers? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We didn’t see the British or any other Europeans. Because the British were all in Europe. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ah yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...or North Africa or whatever. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The only foreign troops that we ever had in Australia to my knowledge...and you could be able to confirm it, were the Americans. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok. Umm, the question is, “did you witness...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I’m sorry, did you witness what?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: “Did you witness any battles or violence?” But you haven’t right?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, no sorry. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It’s ok. (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, I have never witness anybody but I think they used to be, when you read about this, there were a certain amount of... And certainly in Brisbane...not up in Rockhampton...there were a certain amount of ill-feelings between the Australian and American troops.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What’s that?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sorry, you’re right?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: ...Ill-feelings? What? Sorry.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ill-feelings. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Bad feeling.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The Australians didn’t think too highly of the Americans...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhhh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The term is “ill-feelings” Meaning that they didn’t feel well...you know...because of all the young women were going out with the American soldiers. (giggle)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: (laugh)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And you know, the Australians...they more had to take second place! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hahaha. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The Americans were, you know, entertaining the Australian women. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh..</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I mean I wasn’t exposed to that because I was a six, seven, or eight year old kid. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That wasn’t about me.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You know, I heard about that later.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh. I see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So that’s not directly relevant. So the answer to that question is no. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I didn’t witness anything.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Are there any other stories from this time period that you would like to share with me? Anything else!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...No. I’m trying to think... Ahh. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Dad, did you tell Jack the reason why you don’t like sweet potato now?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh yeah! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh no. That does not have to do with the war. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That does not have to do with the war. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Ok, sorry.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, I’ll tell you that afterwards. I’m trying to think, the only thing I remember is one time, there was a well-known pilot, and he was flying this plane...I don’t know what kind of aircraft. But it was called G for George. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: What?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: G for George. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was well known. And he was a well known pilot. So he flew over Rockhampton. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (typing) </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: And he were out, just looking at this plane as it flew over. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohhh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and I mean really, if you Google, “G for George”, on the computer, you would probably find out about the story behind it. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t know.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I will look it up. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I don’t...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Was it called “G” or called “G for George”?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It’s called, “G for George”!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: (laugh)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: G for George!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, G for George!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: G for George. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: That’s cool.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, it’s not just called “G”. It’s called “G for George”!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Google, “G for George” and see what comes up!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, I will. I will google it. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It will be interesting because he was a well-known pilot at Park Ave. where we saw. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: G for George...I think I found it already! Wow. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Have you?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, G for George. Ok, it’s a...let’s see....I will read it. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Can you Google it while talking to me?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. Ok, “G for George flew 90 operational missions over Germany and occupied Europe during the height of the bomber offensive. From the time it was built in 1942 until its retirement from active service in 1944, the bomber was flown by Number 460 Squadron...” </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Squadron.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, squadron. R-A-A-F. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: R double A F which stand for the Royal Australian Air Force. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...(cannot be understood)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: A beg your pardon?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Does it say that it was particularly flown by any pilot? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, let’s see. Pilot... Um, Alec Saintsmith. Alec Saintsmith. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, the name doesn’t mean anything. But there, that’s it aircraft, it flew over! (giggles)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Wow! Ha!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Do you remember it Dad? Remember seeing it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yes! </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: There is a photo with the Australian Prime Minister, Mr. Curtin?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Curtin. C-U-R-T-I-N. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh no. Harry Tickle. No I don’t know, he is the Grand Staff Engineer, responsible for the main...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Maintenance.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah...maintenance, for the bomber, G for George. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: There! I remembered something correctly!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I thought it might have been one, but it could be different pilots. That plane definitely flew over. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It was all over Germany right?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...so it must of made..come home to Australia and then because it was such a you know, well-known aircraft. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Today it is displayed in the Anzac Hall at the Australia War Memorial in Canberra. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh, is it? I would have to remember that!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I would have to go and see it.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Right, that was my little trip about that! G for George.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, thank you! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: What else do you want to ask?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Is there anything that you would like to tell the younger generations about your experience WW2 or about war in general?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well, I don’t have any...well I was a kid, you know...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You have asked me before...I forgot...I’ll answer this question now. No, I don’t particularly remember...anything that I sorta wanna pass on...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...as a child. My experiences were really normal and broad except that you know, things were a bit rationed but we were never hungry. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were never hungry, we just had to ration...and the good that we had were simple. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: But then, yes, war in general...well, yes. War in general is...is just...how can I put it? It should not be contemplated. Just look at the war in Afghanistan, and the war in Iraq. And people are...you know....people have been...you know....people have been sent to war and the senseless slaughter and the loss of lives. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...and on all sides. So, there is no reason for war. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...except if someone invaded a country, well then the people who are living there quite entitle to do something...to parts...bits of their country. To go off with you know whats the word...oh...to declare war on someone...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Self-defense isn’t it?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Well I said in defense. There is no, yes, reason really...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam:...for war cause you know, just so many, so many innocent people and even the troops are killed and just look at it. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We just had Anzac Day which reminded us...reminds us of the senseless war....organized or determined by the British officers. They did not have much idea what they were doing quite frankly. People were just sent...as we say, lands to the slaughter. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: There is no real...no real...no reason for war. Things have to be resolved without war but as I said, the only thing is ahh...naturally, a country is invaded. Those people are entitled to try to defend themselves. They can’t just sit there and let the invader take their land. You know?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. I know what you mean. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The one you asked me before, you alright with that one?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A happy moment did you say, did you ask me some question about that somewhere along the...?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, I asked you, “What’s was one of the...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...happy memories. I remember when peace in the pacific was declared. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, when...(typing)...so that was August 15...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The war end on August 15, 1945. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, August 15, 1945. That is when the Japanese emperor spoke to the...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I remember that because, this lad...who lived around the corner in the next street, he was older than I am, rode a bicycle down our street...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...towing an empty kerosene can which was like a...would hold a... Four gallons, do you have things in gallons or liters over there in Japan?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Liters.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong> </strong><em>Brian Balaam: Liters. So, there was about...how many liters are in a gallon? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: I will calculate it right now. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Roughly, roughly.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Three is it?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Four or something. Is it?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It’s ok...one liter is 0.26417 US gallons. Ok, wait, gallons to liters right? (door bell ringing) Ok Pops, it is 3.7 liters.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Isn’t it 3?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: 3.8 actually. 3.8 liters. (doorbell ringing again)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: one...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: One gallon is 3.8 liters. Roughly. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So in other words, the kerosene...so he was towing an empty 15 liter...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...on his bicycle. Just to make a noise...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...to celebrate that peace has arrived. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: So...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: This boy rode his bike down our street...a gravel street. So this empty kerosene drum which was a square, it was a square in those days which was big enough to carry 15~16 liters, it was bouncing off the back of his bike and this other younger lad was running behind him and we put up strings of paper flags. Those days, you couldn’t even get a flag, the Australian flag. You couldn’t get a flag during the war years made out of material.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So they were all paper flags. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, paper flags. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, made out of paper, you know?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So there were little paper flags in front of our house in Rockhampton on the front verandah between two posts flying...well they were just hanging like a banner, to celebrate peace. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wow. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So...I don’t think you are aware of it, originally, that date of August was called, “VJ Day” which stood for “Victory over Japan” </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: VJ Day.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: VJ Day, Victory over Japan. But more recent years, it was changed to try and be more sensitive to the Japanese, they changed it to VP Day which is Victory over the Pacific. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You with me?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. So Victory to Japan Day to Victory in the Pacific Day. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Victory over the Pacific, yes.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The other one is called the VE Day which is Victory in...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Europe!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: ...which would some time in was it in May?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yes, May. Let’s see. V...(Googling “VE Day”)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Did your mother get went to get the door?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. VE Day is um May 8th. But in Commonwealth countries it is May 7th. Why, I don’t know why. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We remember this as students at that time, students of a Catholic school, we always thought it was just one of those unusual things that victory in the Pacific was declared on the feast of the Assumption. The Assumption</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Feast of the Assumption. And you could look up the calendar in May, interesting, Europe was declared on the feast of the Assumption. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh so it’s...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You look it up!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (laugh)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: A-S-S-U-M-P-T-I-O-N. </em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, victory...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So, victory in Europe was declared on the feast of the Assumption. Thereabouts. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, let’s see.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The feast of the Assumptions...you know the nuns made a point of this at our Catholic school. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, haha.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I still remember that! I might be wrong, well I would have to access a Catholic calendar which you probably could. 1945 to find out when the feast of the Assumption was. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Let’s see. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Call that out. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Catholic calendar. Let’s see...I got a Catholic calendar. Catholic calendar...is it the Roman Catholic Saints...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: What?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Um... </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That will do. The Roman Catholic calendar... </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, let’s see. July...Feast in the...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: 1945 you gotta get cause the feast changes each year.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. Feast...1945. (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Noe you gotta get the Feast of the Assumption. A-S-S-U-M-P-T-I-O-N. Which date was it? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: 8th of July...wait...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: No, it’s not July...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wait, what are we trying to find again?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The Feast of the Assumption. A-S-S-P</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: -T-I-O-N. In 1945. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: (typing) Ok, the Feast of the Assumption, 1945. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: What date?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It was...um...(pause) I can’t find it...May 20!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh, is it?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Something like that...yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh..well, we are wrong then. We were always told that is was close to the Feast of the Assumption. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Wait, in 1945...um um um...yeah that’s it.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: If you could look up Easter. When was Easter in 1945?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, Easter in 1945. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: The Assumption is 40 days after Easter. I can work it out then. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, Easter 1945...was April 1st. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: April 1st?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup. Which means, it was the 21st? </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Sorry?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: In 1945, Easter Day was April the 1st. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Alright, so that is 30. There, that is 38 days. We are saying the Feast of the Assumption but it was close to it.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: We were always told that.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Hmm.</strong>\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: So that is what they saying, the...did they say the victory was the 8th of May? Was it? 1945.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, and I think that is when the kamikaze attacked...wait the kamikaze (Googling “kamikaze attacks”) You know Pops, when you were living Rockhampton, did you hear anything about what happened in...Darwin?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Ahh...I don’t remember that.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: How many people died in Darwin? Let’s see...</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, I don’t know. I can’t remember that, Jack. Sorry. (Skype sound)</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Darwin...Japanese...attack (typing)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I think there were 100 0r something. Weren\'t there? </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: The bombing of Darwin. It was on February 19th, 1942. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Yeah, I don’t think...I think it was kept fairly quiet.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: “It was the first and the largest single attack by a foreign power against Australia.” </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That’s right.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, there were 240 Japanese aircraft attacked ships in Darwin’s harbor and umm...let’s see...how many people died?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: It was over 100 I think. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: 250~320 killed.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Oh, my goodness. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: ...and ten ships were sunk, 23 aircrafts destroyed...yeah. So, that’s it. That’s sad.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: How many ships sunk? How many ships were sunk?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ahh...ten. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: Goodness.</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: And 20 damaged. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They just celebrated...commemorated, not celebrated...the 70th anniversary, you see...</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, really?</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: In Darwin. Oh, yes. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Do they do that every year?</strong>\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: No, 70 years.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Oh, yeah it is 70 years!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: It was 42 and now it is 2012 so...\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ohh.</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: They may have an annual commemoration but this year was the 70th. And I don\'t remember hearing anything and I think the federal government kept it quiet so not to panic the people. I think you may find that, but I’m not sure. </em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Ok, thank you!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: My iPad is down to 17%, I have to go charge it. How is it going?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: It’s good, it’s good. I just finished! Well, thank you for your time!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: I’m not trying to get rid of you but I just looked up...I’m down to 16%, we would have to recharge. </em>\r\n\r\n<em> </em>\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yeah, you should. </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Is it ok? You asked everything?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: You sure?</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Yup!</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Very interesting Dad! (claps)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Thank you very much! (claps)</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<em>Brian Balaam: That’s alright!</em>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Hurray!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Thank you Pops! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nTherese Adachi: Hurray!\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Jack Adachi: Thank you for your time! </strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', '', 0, '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '1877-revision-4', '', '', '2012-05-28 09:56:18', '2012-05-28 13:56:18', '', 1877, 'http://localhost:8888/benmerde2012/2012/05/1877-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0) ;
